725887f-a.text:
148th Street (Tyndall Street), between Jamaica and Archer Aves., showing in the foreoround the Adikes freight station. Peyond it, facing on 148th Street is the four story frame structure occupied by this family and used as a wholesale distributing house for groceries, grains, seeds etc. Henry Adikes flour mill.located on 148th Street, was established in 1855. In 1883 it stood opposite the Long Island Railroad station. The buildings in this view do not appear in 1931.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

727024f-c.text:
Jamaica Ave., north side, opposite 148th Street (formerly Brandford,also known as Tyndall Street), showing the Belknap house of 1891 in a set of three views. John Adikes was the next owner.
May 1923.
View 2: October 1923.
View 3: April 1929.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

727023f-a.text:
Jamaica Avenue, north side, between 148th and 149th Streets. This frame mansion was owned by A.A. De Grauw in 1909.
P. L Sperr  March 10, 1927

727030f-b.text:
Jamaica Ave., north side, west of 150th to 148th Streets, showing in views 1 and 2 the Reformed Church Parsonage, erected by the Church in 1853 at a coat of ~6500. It was sold in January 1924 and demolished in July of that year; being occupied by the Rev. R.E. Wicks D.D., prior to its sale. View No. 3 shows in addition, in their order from the Parsonage, the 9. Hoyt and Davis
homes of 1891.
1922.
Views 1 and 2.
View 3: 1923.
Nugene L. Armbruster Collection.
